My gut feel is that I'm not too impressed with this tool to start with.  I looked at it before and decided not to implement anything around it.  For the most part it does two things for us:

1. Remove tabs.
2. Sort variable names in some way.

I'm fine with #1.  #2 seems only moderately useful.  The most irritating thing about it to me is that it moves all of the FILESEXTRAPATHS in our bbappend files from the top to somewhere randomly in the middle, yet this is something every single bbappend file has and really belongs at the top.

The primary thing I'd like out of a linter / formatter is that multi-line variables are broken out (and indented) in a consistent way and ideally sorted.  If the only thing we had was something that parsed DEPENDS and RDEPENDS and turned them into something like this I'd be way happier than what this tool is doing:

  DEPENDS = " \
      bar \
      foo \
      "
 
 (I don't even care the exact formatting as long as we can get something consistent and sorted.)

That's probably pretty trivial to fix and seems reasonable to me.  It's not clear the formatter was originally intended to be used on bbappend files, so this is probably just a miss.  ACK.

This was exactly my original impetus for wanting a standard formatter, but the current oe-sylize doesn't yet support the above, so my plan was to get some concensus on "should we stylize?"  then we can go add features like the above.  If we don't think the key ordering is valuable, we could make it optional, although I do like that the files are consistent, which I think helps in the quick-turn readability.


Overall my position is "we should have a consistent format", and I don't have a strong opinion as to what that format is, just that I want to mash a key in vim and make my bitbake files "correct" in terms of spacing and other stuff.

> If we don't think the key ordering is valuable, we could make it optional, although I do like that the
files are consistent, which I think helps in the quick-turn readability.

For simple recipes, where there were only one copy of each variable, I think a stable sorting would be just fine.  For complex ones there can be cases where it is much easier to understand by not sorting.

```
FOO ?= "foo" # baseline

# Add some configs for 'machine'.
FOO:append:machine = "machine-foo"
BAR:append:machine = "machine-bar"

# Depending on the class we have an extra.
FOO:append:class-native = "native-foo"
FOO:append:class-target = "target-foo"
```

Trying to put all the 'BAR's together first and then all the 'FOO's together would separate intent.

Just like you wouldn't sort your variables and functions in a struct by name, I don't think sorting Yocto variables by name is usually helpful.

The meta-phosphor/recipes-phosphor/fans/phosphor-fan_git.bb is an overly complicated recipe to begin with, and would ideally be simplified, but it is a good example here of how this script destroys intent and makes it even harder to read.

Agreed, that's really not that great.  I'm betting we can put those smarts into the script.  Arguably I would say that duplicated parameters should be sorted by :class-target/native, then :machine THEN keyname.  That seems pretty reasonable to code into the script.  I can take a look.

Anything is better than nothing here, IMO.

Latest patch addresses a couple things.

FILEEXTRAPATHS is now kept at the top, which seems to minimize the wrong-looking changes made to bbappend files.  This was just a matter of adding it to the script key list.  Previously it was doing it alphabetically, which is why the key was moving so far down.

I also added support for a comment of
# oe-stylize ignore

which if found anywhere in the file, will stop the script from formatting, and I added that line to phosphor-fan_git.bb to keep that context.  I did a quick skim of other spots where we have that pattern, and I didn't see any.... maaaaaaybe meta-phosphor/recipes-phosphor/state/phosphor-state-manager_git.bb, but I personally think the formatted one is better in that case.

I looked at all the files and tried to flag anything that looked strange.  Not necessarily hung up on any of it, but at least now I should be able to do diff-to-diff reviews instead of trying to go through these 800 files again.
Thanks for reviewing.  That gives me the feedback I need to keep hammering stuff out.

In terms of making incremental progress on this, could we remove the diff on any file (including the ones that currently have oe-stylize ignore) from this patchset for which there's still a question of formatting, and get the bulk of the non-controversial, simple changes on master?  I think the bulk of the changes to the simple recipes are good, and improve our examples for folks adding new changes.  This is something we can iterate on over time as we make stylize better.  I can split up every diff that had a comment into patch #2, which should hopefully also make it easier to review, and I can start nailing those down.
